	<h3>2. Lights, camera, funded! - Creating a great introduction video</h3>
	<hr>
	<iframe  class="pagination-centered" width="853" height="480" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/PJ6a-WkTIjw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
	<br><br>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Check out this great introduction video for the <a href="https://r10plus.uair.co/r10">R10+ from UAir</a>.</p><br>
	  <p>Engaging, well-produced introduction videos are vital to the success of crowdfunding campaigns. We've listed out some do's and don'ts for you to keep in mind as you create your own video.</p><br>
	</blockquote>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Make a great video by doing all of the following:</p><br>
	  <ul>
	  	<li>Introduce the product or idea (reason for funding) at the beginning of the video.</li>
	  	<li>Introduce yourself and your team. Explain why you are passionate about raising the money and why you're the right team to run the campaign.</li>
	  	<li>Make sure to talk about the rewards generally. There's no need to review every level of rewards if you have more than two or three.</li>
	  	<li>Utilize background music, a tripod, and an external microphone if possible to ensure professionalism in the final product.</li>	  	
	  </ul>
	</blockquote>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Things to avoid when making your video:</p><br>
	  <ul>
	  	<li>Recording just your face ("The floating head" video) talking about your project for two minutes. This isn't engaging and we know you're more creative than that!</li>
	  	<li>Ending with just a "thank you" and no call-to-action. Make sure you end with a clear ask (e.g. "We're excited for you to join our campaign! Just click the 'Contribute' button to the right and we'll be in touch soon.") </li>
	  	<li>Not making a video and using a picture instead. This is lame! You'll have much more success throughout your campaign with a great intro video. Have incredible photos you want to use? They belong in the body description section.</li>		  	
	  </ul>	  
	</blockquote>
