	<h3>3. Shape up - Create a killer campaign body description</h3>
	<hr>
	<center><img src="/assets/body_description.png"></center>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Check out this great body description content for the <a href="https://r10plus.uair.co/r10">R10+ from UAir</a>.</p><br>
	  <p>Well-designed, colorful, and concise content in the body of your Crowdhoster campaign is a <em>huge</em> part of reaching (and exceeding) your funding goal. Here are a couple of tips to help you polish your body content and avoid common "campaign killer" pitfalls:</p><br>
	</blockquote>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Great body descriptions do the following:</p><br>
	  <ul>
	  	<li>Recap the content of the introduction video. Remind your potential contributors of the product / idea / reason for raising funds and the background of you and/or your team.</li>
	  	<li>Use lots of awesome images! Creating a super thin wallet? Show some high-res shots of the wallet in action. Raising money for a trip? Share pictures of a map detailing where you plan to travel and photos of the hostels you hope to stay at.</li>
	  	<li>Address risk. Some campaigns, especially those that are manufacturing a product, are susceptible to risks in delivery of rewards. If your campaign has the potential to be delayed or derailed by a third party (e.g. manufacturer in China), be sure to tell your potential contributors about it. They will appreciate your candidness.</li> 	
	  </ul>
	</blockquote>
	<blockquote>
	  <p>Avoid these common body description pitfalls:</p><br>
	  <ul>
	  	<li>Text-only descriptions. Don't bore your potential contributors!</li>
	  	<li>Blurry images, images you find via a Google Image search, or irrelevant images (e.g. memes). Keep your images legal and professional</li>
	  	<li>Failing to update your body description content throughout the campaign. Be sure to update your potential contributors about all the traction you've already seen, especially if you've added new rewards/perks by exceeding your "tilt" goal.</li>		  	
	  </ul>	  
	</blockquote>
